  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by concealing its true origin. This is typically done through complex financial transactions that make it difficult to trace the money back to its illegal source.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and amended in 2018. The law imposes stringent regulations on financial institutions to detect and report suspicious transactions, and it establishes severe penalties for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering activities.\n\nChinese authorities, including the People's Bank of China and other regulatory bodies, actively work to combat money laundering and other financial crimes in accordance with the law, ensuring the stability and integrity of the financial system.",
